{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bb75c0d7-c1e9-4cf5-b51c-f3d1f3696ac7","content":"In .NET MAUI, `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` **still exist** on the `Application` class and work the same way. However, the recommended modern approach is to use **Window lifecycle events**.\n\n**Option 1 — Override `CreateWindow` in `App.xaml.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Platform-specific events via `MauiProgram.cs`:**\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnStart((activity) => { /* ... */ })\n        .OnStop((activity) => { /* ... */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .OnActivated((app) => { /* ... */ })\n        .DidEnterBackground((app) => { /* ... */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**TL;DR:** Your existing overrides will compile and run. Migrate to `Window` events if you need per-window granularity, or to `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` if you need platform-specific hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c25aeafa-5adc-4ec4-9447-80e6d28eed1f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` in your `Application` subclass.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. The `Application` class in MAUI still has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` — but the recommended approach is to use the cross-platform lifecycle events via `CreateWindow` override or the platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`.\n\n\nWhile those methods still work for backward compatibility, the modern approach leverages `Window` lifecycle events instead — mapping `OnStart` to `Window.Created`, `OnSleep` to `Window.Deactivated` or `Window.Stopped`, and `OnResume` to `Window.Activated`.","outputTokens":752,"requestId":"9547:397A40:13A08FB:1610C2E:6A067116"},"id":"42ee5019-141d-4910-98cc-8d9e5ff94c61","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:04:38.016Z","parentId":"6190669b-049d-4c9a-b5d6-2372be07ee05"}
